ROMAN RELIGION

The religion of the early Romans was much more staid and sober than that ol the Greeks, and had little or none of that poetical expansiveness which characterizedthe latter. It reflected merely the interests oi a people engaged ior the most part in tilling the soil, breeding cattle, and making ψ war.

lavor or displeasure by varying atmospheric phenomena: clear sky or storm, thunder, lightning, or hail. That this was the original conception ol Jupiter is shown among other things ¹by the common phrase, sub Jove esse, to be in
